        "name": "Resources",
        "text": "1. [Hawthorne](http://www.pem.org/sites/hawthorne/#), Peabody Essex Museum. \r\n2. “[A Red Hot ‘A’ and a Lusting Divine: Sources for *The Scarlet Letter*](http://www.hampton.lib.nh.us/hampton/biog/bachilerscarletletter.htm),” by Frederick Newberry, *New England Quarterly* via Lane Memorial Library.  \r\n3. [Hawthorne in Salem](http://www.hawthorneinsalem.org/), North Shore Community College. "
      },
      {
        "name": "Overview",
        "text": "In a society governed by Puritans, Hester Prynne is an outcast. Why? Because she had a baby...out of wedlock. (Gasp!) Nathaniel Hawthorne’s *The Scarlet Letter*, published in 1850, sets its events in the Puritan society of two centuries before, and narrates a tale as scandalous for that time as the stuff in grocery-store paperbacks now. So why is this novel considered one of the greatest American novels, and why do we study it in schools? Hawthorne wrote in the tradition of romanticism, a term used to describe literature that emphasizes individualism and emotion, uses both imagery and symbolism, and looks into humanity’s darker impulses and desires. In *The Scarlet Letter*, Hawthorne’s romanticism helps him to critique the hypocrisy of the Puritan religion while also exploring more universal themes of self-consciousness, desire, revenge, shame, and guilt. The result made for one of the first mass-produced books in America, and a volume still on many high schools’ required reading lists today. This primary source set includes photographs, paintings, documents, maps, and items that relate both to the setting of *The Scarlet Letter*, the Massachusetts Bay Colony in the mid-seventeenth century, and thematic elements within the book."
      }
